📄 EFK Stack on Minikube (Elasticsearch + Fluent Bit + Kibana)

This guide installs a complete logging stack on Kubernetes (Minikube):

Elasticsearch (log storage + search)
Kibana (UI dashboard)
Fluent Bit (log collector)
⚙️ 1. Prerequisites
Minimum system requirements
CPU: 4+ cores (you have 12 ✔)
RAM: 8GB+ (you have ~11GB ✔)
Disk: 20GB+ free ✔
Tools required
Minikube
kubectl
Helm
Docker driver for Minikube

Check:

minikube version
kubectl version --client
helm version
🚀 2. Start Minikube
minikube start --cpus=4 --memory=8192

Verify:

kubectl get nodes
📦 3. Create Namespace
kubectl create namespace logging
📊 4. Install Elasticsearch
Add Helm repo
helm repo add elastic https://helm.elastic.co
helm repo update
Create values file
mkdir -p ~/efk-lab
cd ~/efk-lab
cat > elasticsearch-values.yaml <<EOF
replicas: 1

minimumMasterNodes: 1

resources:
  requests:
    cpu: "500m"
    memory: "1Gi"
  limits:
    cpu: "2"
    memory: "2Gi"

esJavaOpts: "-Xms1g -Xmx1g"

volumeClaimTemplate:
  accessModes:
    - ReadWriteOnce
  resources:
    requests:
      storage: 5Gi
EOF
Install Elasticsearch
helm install elasticsearch elastic/elasticsearch \
  -n logging \
  -f elasticsearch-values.yaml \
  --wait --timeout 15m
Verify
kubectl get pods -n logging
kubectl get pvc -n logging

Test:

kubectl port-forward -n logging svc/elasticsearch-master 9200:9200
curl -k https://localhost:9200 -u elastic:<PASSWORD>

Get password:

kubectl get secret -n logging elasticsearch-master-credentials \
  -o jsonpath="{.data.password}" | base64 -d; echo
📊 5. Install Kibana
IMPORTANT (avoid Helm issues)

Always use:

helm install kibana elastic/kibana \
  -n logging \
  --wait --timeout 15m \
  --set resources.requests.memory=512Mi \
  --set resources.limits.memory=1Gi \
  --set elasticsearchHosts="https://elasticsearch-master:9200"
Verify
kubectl get pods -n logging
Access Kibana
kubectl port-forward -n logging svc/kibana-kibana 5601:5601

Open:

http://localhost:5601

Login:

user: elastic
password: (same as Elasticsearch secret)
📥 6. Install Fluent Bit (Log Collector)
helm repo add fluent https://fluent.github.io/helm-charts
helm repo update

Install:

helm install fluent-bit fluent/fluent-bit -n logging

Verify:

kubectl get pods -n logging
🧪 7. Generate Test Logs
kubectl run log-test \
  --image=busybox \
  --restart=Never \
  -- sh -c 'while true; do echo "EFK test log $(date)"; sleep 2; done'
📊 8. View Logs in Kibana

Open Kibana:

http://localhost:5601

Go to:

Discover → Create Data View

Use index:

fluentbit-*

Set time range:

Last 15 minutes
View logs 🎉
🧹 9. Cleanup (optional)
helm uninstall fluent-bit -n logging
helm uninstall kibana -n logging
helm uninstall elasticsearch -n logging
kubectl delete namespace logging
⚠️ Common Issues
1. Helm timeout

Fix:

--wait --timeout 15m
2. Kibana stuck

Delete job:

kubectl delete jobs -n logging --all
3. Empty Kibana logs

Check Fluent Bit:

kubectl logs -n logging <fluent-bit-pod>
🎯 Architecture
Kubernetes Pods
      ↓
Fluent Bit (log collector)
      ↓
Elasticsearch (storage)
      ↓
Kibana (visualization)
🚀 Done

You now have a production-style logging pipeline on Kubernetes (Minikube).
